Let’s not forget about the policing of pupil referral units either, many of which have been architecturally built to mimic prisons. And how young Black girls in particular are treated whilst they’re there.

Teachers who feel like they’ve lost control or can’t ‘humble’ a student, opt for humiliation and scare tactics. I literally had a teacher punch a wall next to my face whilst shouting in my face when I was in college, the class saw. Nothing happened. I got kicked out of class.

People think that because someone is a ‘teacher’ it means they are well intentioned and care about young people. But a lot of them don’t, outside of the label of teacher, they exist as individuals who bring their racist & discriminatory beliefs with them into the classroom

I can’t stop thinking about Child Q. The fact the teachers called the police despite already searching her belongings, clearly shows it wasn’t about the suspected cannabis. It was the fact the teachers were mad they couldn’t ‘catch her out’ & wanted to scare her in retaliation

RT @bg_bookclub: Ask me again why we wrote Grown? 

Black girls being perceived as big women and treated as such can be a matter of life an…

I could speak on this for ages but honestly for now all I’ll say is @Ebinehita_ has BEEN doing the work on calling out institutions for the mistreatment of Black girls and continues to provide important spaces for Black girls with @MilkHoneyBees and @Juvenis

Of course this doesn’t refer to ‘all’ Black male teachers, I’ve met some that are incredible. However you can’t act blind to the fact that misogyny, specifically misogynoir is all too often perpetuated by Black men, inside and outside of educational institutions

It’s important to point out that I’ve had a handful of experiences in particular with Black male teachers who perpetuate & are often the driving force behind the stereotypes & justification of the mistreatment of black girls in schools, especially if they’re in the senior team.

The amount of times I’ve had to call our teachers for their treatment of black girls is wild. If they’re quiet? They’re aggressive. Loud? They’re rude. Friendly? They’re promiscuous. Curious? They’re challenging authority. Things have BEEN needing to change

Some more extracts I found, the pictures are terrible because they’re from 2016 😅, but the words are just as important.

I’d highly recommend people to read this book, it had a huge influence on my approach to youth work within schools & outside too

https://t.co/JT8TwSpYB1 https://t.co/E1ounXGQDh

There’s a book called Pushout: The criminalisation of Black girls in schools by Monique W Morris that I read years ago; that touches on this exact topic, albeit through an American lens.

Anyways, for anyone Black who has ADHD, spaces like @adhdbabes exist to provide you with the affirmation that you are not alone in your discomfort and ADHD is shit for everybody. But equally, a reminder that we experience immense amounts of joy because of it

Moral of the story, an 'official' ADHD diagnosis does not 'fix' you or immediately improve your life.

Things will feel harder & u'll confront wounds you've long forgotten about

BUT, give yourself the grace to work through the discomfort, and I promise you it will get better

Getting diagnosed with ADHD literally unearthed a lot of trauma/experiences that I had shoved into the deep oblivion of my subconscious. It opened up WOUNDS that I never knew existed. But WHEW, my diagnosis was the catalyst for a huge shift in the care/love I extended to myself

Getting diagnosed is one thing, but the process of working through the fact you've gone undiagnosed throughout your childhood/early adulthood, and acknowledging all the ways you've been gaslit, failed and robbed of compassion/understanding? THAT SHIT HURTS

I will always say, the emotional/mental impact of having undiagnosed ADHD has always been the biggest hurdle I've had to work through. Before I was diagnosed I literally cried maybe like 5 times a year. But once I started to process my diagnosis? I cried every day for 3 months 🥴

This is spot on. Being diagnosed helped me to understand just how much  shame I had internalised from being made to feel like my reactions/behaviours were 'too much' or 'not the norm'. Unlearning and unpacking it has been HARD but has literally changed me completely https://t.co/7NShpPoN0I

As of last year, my hormone fluctuations around my menstrual cycle started fucking up differently and these days I usually end up in hospital 🥴🥴🥴 each month it’s like a lucky dip of new symptoms. From seizures to extreme abdominal pain 🤪 love that for me oxox

When you deep it, people who menstruate are continuously gaslit out of our period pains and the emotional turmoil we go through with our hormone fluctuations, by workforce’s and managers who want to diminish our experiences just so we show up to work

One of my old colleagues, an older Black lesbian woman, was the first person I’ve seen set strict work boundaries around working when she’s on her period. As in she wouldn’t. The first two days of her period, she would not come to work. That changed it all for me tbh https://t.co/9VFBDIsDOz

Anyways, as I said Exist Loudly will be doing the ✨bare minimum✨ And celebrating ourselves every step of the way. A return to joy.  Can’t wait x

So many of us who do community work live in a constant state of burn out. We are constantly battling with our own internal expectations and those placed on us by community and it’s not only tiring but robs you of your ‘why’ behind starting the work in the first place.

I read this book called ‘Sustaining spirit’ by Naomi Ortiz when I had just got out of hospital and was unable to walk unaided. This book genuinely helped shift my perspective and extend grace to myself when I needed it most https://t.co/Rc8OyA8Umx

It is so easy when you do community work to burn yourself out and for many, it’s expected of you to. We often make ourselves overly responsible for the needs of our community because we care, yet we refuse to extend that same care back to ourselves

My health meant I was forced to re-think and reflect on my work with Exist Loudly. The reality is that I lived in consistent burn out but the difference now is I quite literally can’t do that anymore or I’ll end up back in hospital again.

My adhd genuinely makes waiting for things outside of my control actually excruciating
I’ve been stuck on a train for 2 hours…. The train was only mean to take 20 mins. These two little kids are crying next to me and I am THIS close to crying with them

Anyways, I've been reading up a lot around the Non-profit industrial complex, the impact of neo-liberalism on the sector and the barriers to navigating the non profit sector as a Black person working on the ground and as a Black led organisation and WHEW. SO MANY WORDS TO SAY

The narrative that youth workers should be able to 'handle' any & every form of trauma that arises within your work, on the basis that it's 'a part of the job' is a dangerous one & one that is often held up by people who only see youth as 'numbers' for their impact reports

It’s so mad that so many youth organisations who work with youth who are navigating serious trauma, don’t provide free therapy for their staff beyond a ‘call this number’ service. This should be the bare minimum investment employers make for their staff on the ground
Therapy has definitely made me a better youth worker as well.
Over 2 years I’ve been in consistent weekly therapy and I really can’t believe how much it’s changed me and my outlook on so many aspects of my life
Therapy has truly changed my life, my therapist is legit a god send

So often young LGBTQ+ people end up in an echo chamber of people justifying or dismissing their parents violent & abusive homophobic behaviour & telling them to just ‘get on with it’. So im glad I can be the person to tell them their parents are moving mad and its not their fault

Anyways, this happens throughout the charity sector & isn't just specific to LGBTQ+ youth orgs. The charity sector in itself is built on white saviourism and many charities are started by rich yt people who 'wanted a change' after working in the corporate banks for years xox https://t.co/MwLcLG3PaT

Moral of the story is, you'll notice a lot of these LGBTQ+ youth non-profits/charities push their young service users to partake in interviews surrounding their trauma so they can show 'how impactful the org is', when in fact it's just inflating their white saviour complex xox

Even when I did the ITV interview for Pride in Britain,it featured 1 of my YP & I strictly gave the reporter rules beforehand that they were not allowed to ask anything to do with coming out/trauma related stories. No doubt that's why they only featured briefly in the final cut

You'll even notice in the Ch4 mini doc I did, there was no images, interviews or pictures of young people there. Only illustrations. Why? Because I refused to do so. They kept pushing and I pushed back and threatened to pull the video. I don't play around with this

This has happened multiple times even outside of this week, Reporter: "Hey we want stories of homeless Black young people, can you give us some" 
Me: No
Reporter: "hey you were homeless can you give us your story instead"
Me: Piss off

If it isn't already clear, Exist Loudly is not one of these non-profits/charities that will exploit their young people by pushing them to do interviews that in no way benefit them, in order to 'build relationships' with media outlets with the hope of getting funding. Fuck off

Equally, WHY is it that you only want to cover stories around NB youth because a celeb has 'come out' as non binary? Why didn't you try to cover these stories when the government were robbing trans and nb youth of their rights? Oh that's right, you were too busy platforming TERFs

Listen, it's amazing to see people, no matter their social status step into their authentic selves. HOWEVER, lets not be obtuse and act as though because a rich celeb feels safe to tell the world about their NB identity, that transphobia and homophobia is solved

"inspired by Demi Lovato coming out as non binary we wanted to speak to other non binary young people about their pronouns, can you put some forward" ABSOLUTELY NOT. The media world is a cruel and unforgiving place for young trans & nb people and they are not props for your story

I'm going to make this clear from now to any journalists, DO NOT reach out to me to request me to put forward young people for your mainstream media platforms for interviews around their identity or 'coming out stories'. I will never do this. Fuck off
